It seems like you are asking for a macro that searches for and exports passwords from an office document to an ArrayList in Java. Here's a basic example of how you could do that using Apache POI, a popular library for handling Microsoft Office documents in Java:

First, you need to add Apache POI to your project. If you're using Maven, you can add the following dependency to your pom.xml:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.apache.poi</groupId>
    <artifactId>poi-ooxml</artifactId>
    <version>5.2.2</version>
</dependency>
```

Next, you can create a class that uses Apache POI to read an Excel document and store the passwords in an ArrayList:

```java
import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.*;
import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFWorkbook;
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class PasswordExtractor {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Load the Excel document
            FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("path/to/your/passwords.xlsx");
            Workbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook(fis);

            // Create an ArrayList to store the passwords
            ArrayList<String> passwords = new ArrayList<>();

            // Iterate over the sheets in the workbook
            for (Sheet sheet : workbook) {
                // Iterate over the rows in the sheet
                for (Row row : sheet) {
                    // Iterate over the cells in the row
                    for (Cell cell : row) {
                        // Check if the cell contains a password
                        if (cell.getCellType() == CellType.STRING) {
                            String password = cell.getStringCellValue().trim();
                            if (!password.isEmpty()) {
                                passwords.add(password);
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            // Print the passwords
            for (String password : passwords) {
                System.out.println(password);
            }

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

This example reads an Excel document with a password in each cell and stores them in an ArrayList. Make sure to replace "path/to/your/passwords.xlsx" with the path to your actual Excel document.

Laravel middleware is used to filter HTTP requests entering your application. It can be used to perform tasks such as authentication, logging, and session handling.

Here is an example of a Laravel middleware that logs the incoming request to the application's log file:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Http\Middleware;

use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Closure;

class LogRequest
{
    /**
     * Handle an incoming request.
     *
     * @param  \Illuminate\Http\Request  $request
     * @param  \Closure  $next
     * @return \Illuminate\Http\Response|\Illuminate\Http\RedirectResponse
     */
    public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next)
    {
        $log = new \Monolog\Logger('application');
        $log->pushHandler(new \Monolog\Handler\StreamHandler(storage_path('logs/request.log'), \Monolog\Logger::DEBUG));
        $log->addDebug('Received request: '. $request->url());

        $response = $next($request);

        $log->addDebug('Request processed: '. $request->url());

        return $response;
    }
}
```

